SECTION 2: DATABASE ARCHITECTURE ADVICE
================================================================================

QUESTION: Is Supabase the right choice vs self-hosted PostgreSQL/MongoDB/Redis?

CURRENT STATE:
- Docker Compose defines: PostgreSQL 15 + PostGIS 3.3, MongoDB 7, Redis 7, Mosquitto MQTT
- Supabase instance: PostgreSQL 15 + PostGIS 3.3, 11 tables with RLS, 85 wards, 25 agencies
- The architecture doc specifies a 3-tier data model: PostgreSQL (relational/spatial),
  MongoDB (time-series), Redis (caching/sessions)

ANALYSIS:

1. SUPABASE (PostgreSQL + PostGIS) -- RECOMMENDED as primary database

   Why Supabase is the best choice for JUKWA:
   - FREE tier: 500MB database, 1GB file storage, 50K monthly active users, unlimited API requests
   - Open source: Supabase is fully open-source (PostgreSQL + GoTrue + PostgREST + Realtime)
     You can self-host the entire stack if you outgrow the free tier
   - Built-in auth: Email/password, OAuth, magic links -- saves building identity from scratch
   - Row Level Security: Supabase enforces RLS at the database level, not the application level.
     This is the most secure approach -- even if the API is compromised, data stays protected
   - Realtime: Built-in WebSocket subscriptions for live updates (alternative to MQTT for some use cases)
   - PostGIS: Full spatial query support (ST_DWithin, ST_Within, ST_MakePoint) -- critical for
     JUKWA's ward-based routing and proximity alerts
   - Auto-generated REST API: PostgREST gives you CRUD on every table instantly
   - Dashboard: Visual database editor, SQL editor, auth management -- no admin tools needed
   - Kenyan data sovereignty: Supabase runs on AWS. For full sovereignty, self-host in
     Kenya (Safaricom Cloud, Africa Data Centres Nairobi) using the open-source stack

   What Supabase replaces:
   - Self-hosted PostgreSQL + PostGIS (Docker container)
   - Custom auth service (GoTrue replaces the identity-service for auth)
   - API gateway for CRUD (PostgREST replaces basic Fastify CRUD routes)

   What Supabase does NOT replace:
   - MongoDB (time-series telemetry) -- Supabase is relational, not time-series optimized
   - Redis (caching/sessions) -- Supabase has no in-memory cache
   - Mosquitto MQTT (real-time pub/sub) -- Supabase Realtime is WebSocket-based, not MQTT
   - Custom business logic (FSM transitions, AI triage, emergency dispatch)

2. MONGODB (Time-series Telemetry) -- KEEP for traffic data

   MongoDB with time-series collections is purpose-built for the traffic sensor data:
   - High-write throughput (thousands of sensor readings per minute)
   - Schema flexibility (different sensor types send different payloads)
   - Built-in data expiration (auto-delete readings older than 30 days)
   - Aggregation pipeline for traffic pattern analysis

   Recommendation: Keep MongoDB in Docker for traffic telemetry. Do NOT migrate to Supabase.
   If cost is a concern, MongoDB Atlas free tier (512MB) handles this workload.

3. REDIS (Caching/Sessions) -- KEEP but consider Supabase alternatives

   Redis is used for:
   - Session caching (JWT token validation)
   - API response caching (ward lookups, agency directories)
   - Rate limiting

   Recommendation: Keep Redis in Docker. For the MVP, in-memory caching in the Fastify
   services (using Map or lru-cache) may suffice. Add Redis only when scaling beyond
   a single server. Supabase's PostgREST handles caching via HTTP cache headers.

4. MOSQUITTO MQTT (Real-time Pub/Sub) -- KEEP

   MQTT is critical for JUKWA's real-time architecture:
   - Low bandwidth (designed for 3G/satellite connections)
   - QoS guarantees (0=at-most-once, 1=at-least-once, 2=exactly-once)
   - Topic-based security (ACL per topic prefix)
   - Native Android support (HiveMQ MQTT client)

   Supabase Realtime (WebSocket) is NOT a replacement because:
   - WebSockets use more bandwidth than MQTT (important on Safaricom 3G)
   - No QoS guarantees -- messages can be lost on poor connections
   - No topic-level ACL -- all-or-nothing access
   - MQTT is the industry standard for IoT/telemetry (traffic sensors, emergency dispatch)

   Recommendation: Keep Mosquitto. Use Supabase Realtime for citizen-facing features
   (live incident map updates) and MQTT for machine-to-machine communication
   (traffic sensors, emergency dispatch, AI triage results).

RECOMMENDED ARCHITECTURE (Hybrid Supabase + Docker):

  Production:
  - Supabase Cloud (free tier) -- Primary database, auth, REST API, Realtime
  - Docker (self-hosted) -- MongoDB, Redis, Mosquitto, custom Fastify services
  - The Fastify services connect to Supabase PostgreSQL instead of local Docker PostgreSQL

  Development:
  - Docker Compose -- Full local stack including PostgreSQL (for offline dev)
  - Supabase CLI -- Local Supabase instance for testing RLS policies

  Migration path:
  - Phase 1 (MVP): Supabase Cloud for database + auth. Docker for everything else.
  - Phase 2 (Scale): Self-host Supabase on Safaricom Cloud for data sovereignty.
  - Phase 3 (Enterprise): Multi-region PostgreSQL replication for HA.

COST COMPARISON:

  Self-hosted (Docker on VPS):
  - VPS (Hetzner CX21): $7/month
  - Managed PostgreSQL (Supabase free): $0
  - Total: $7/month + maintenance time

  Supabase Free Tier:
  - Database: 500MB (sufficient for MVP with 85 wards + 25 agencies)
  - Auth: 50K MAU
  - Storage: 1GB
  - Bandwidth: 5GB
  - Total: $0/month

  Supabase Pro ($25/month):
  - Database: 8GB
  - Auth: 100K MAU
  - Storage: 100GB
  - Bandwidth: 250GB
  - Total: $25/month

  For a 20-50 user MVP in a single Nairobi ward, the free tier is sufficient.
  Scale to Pro when reaching ~1,000 active users.

